g to innovate new approaches to training talent that, at times, relies on the higher education sector, but increasingly operates independently in order to satisfy talent needs more agilely and effectively. Written primarily for managers, the book focuses on case studies from leading companies, including Google, Ernst & Young, IBM, and Marriott, to illustrate their innovative strategies for talent development across varying levels of individual education, age, and background. The book also addresses professionals on the university side, urging readers to consider the question: Will higher education pivot and adapt, or will it resist change and, therefore, be replaced?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCollege graduatesxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aEmployeesxTraining ofzUnited States. 0aLabor supplyxEffect of education onzUnited States. 0aVocational qualificationszUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Management.2bisacsh  acollege.  ahigher education.  ajobs.  atraining.  auniversity.  avalue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363221940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632219/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles